results.locality: Frankland Island Group, Outcrops of weathered and eroded green and white metamorphic rock, the islands are part of the coastal mountain range separated from the mainland by a rise in sea level. The vegetation on the islands is varied and includes patches of lush dense rainforest, coastal plant communities and mangrove swamps. The islands are very important nesting locations for a number of species of birds which are increasingly threatened by disturbance and habitat destruction elsewhere. Normanby and Russell islands host nesting colonies of pied imperial-pigeons. These white and black birds migrate to Australia from New Guinea each summer to breed and nest on the islands.

Yorkeys Knob (including  Lagoon), Expensive residential area on the coast at the hill called Yorkeys Knob, north of Cairns.  Marina and golf course.  Golf course has an excellent lake, accessible from the road, with an island with trees where cormorants, egrets and other birds breed.

Cairns Esplanade, The foreshore area of Cairns called the Esplanade overlooks the mainly muddy tidal flats with some grassy areas. The area also includes the mangrove swamps on the Northern end of the Esplanade. Easily the best place to observe shorebirds (waders) in comfort from a park bench within the city. Best time for migratory shorebirds is late August-March but some species resident all year.
